  "texts": [
    "As a result, the observed dataset is the union D = D n ∪ D a, consisting of both normal and abnormal instances.",
    "The objective is to effectively identify and exclude the anomalies in D a, so as to learn a model using only the normal instances in D n.To measure the robustness of a rejection threshold based on the quantile of anomaly scores, we define the following function with respect to the loss function: Definition 3.1 (Robustness of a rejection threshold).",
    "Let z:= (x i, y i) ∈ D be a sample and s(z) be an anomaly score such as the reconstruction error ∥x i -f (x i)∥ 2 2, and let s q (z) be the q-quantile of s(z) over D. For a class label ℓ ∈ {0, 1}, we define the subset I:= {z: s q (x i) ∈ [s q1, s q2], y i = ℓ}.",
    "Then L(q 1, q 2, ℓ) = z∈D 1 I (z)s(z) denotes the cumulative sum of scores s(z) in the quantile range [q 1, q 2].",
    "The robustness of a rejection threshold at q-quantile is then defined asR(q) = L(0, q, 0) L(0, 1, 0) - L(0, q, 1) L(0, 1, 1)(1)which quantifies the difference between relative anomaly scores of normal (ℓ = 0) and abnormal (ℓ = 1) instances below the q-quantile."
